<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-803-666  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 803 666.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  August 27 1990 v4 n31 p10(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Business booming to meet DOD needs; firms report increased ordersfor gear for Saudi Arabia. (the US Department of Defense'sOperation Desert Shield)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brewin, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Department of Defense's (DOD's) Operation Desert Shield hascreated great demand for command, control, communications andcomputer equipment among US armed forces, particularly the Armyand Marines, which have deployed developmental and prototypesystems from stateside evaluation sites.andP;  As many as 100,000 UStroops, and perhaps even more, may take part in the operation;sources say the Army may soon be required to set upmainframe-based computer processing centers in Saudi Arabia.andP;  The4th Marine Expeditionary Brigade took 16 rugged C3 Inc computersbased on Intel's 80486 chip to the Middle East, according to aMarine at the Marine Air Ground Task Force's Logistics AutomatedInformation Systems.andP;  The Joint Command Support Element in SaudiArabia deployed several AN/TSC-122 high-frequency radiocommunications central vans, according to a spokesman at RockwellInternational Inc's Collins Defense Communications unit.andP;  Severalother military computer and communication systems used in SaudiArabia are described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MilitaryGovernment AgencyPrototypeApplicationsCommunications TechnologyRuggedized SystemsDemandKuwait-Iraq Conflict, 1990United States. Department of Defense.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>